---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
    title="CSS Anti-pattern Gallery"
    description="Common CSS architecture anti-patterns and modern LSCSS fixes."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Anti-pattern gallery</p>

        <h1>
            CSS anti-pattern gallery
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Common CSS failures often begin as small shortcuts. These examples
            show why they become painful and how LSCSS avoids them.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Deep selectors
        </h2>

        <div class="anti-pattern-pair">
            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--bad">
                <h3>Problem</h3>

<pre><code>.page .wrapper .content .card .title {
    margin: 0;
}</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Deep selectors couple styles to markup structure and become
                    difficult to override.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--good">
                <h3>Fix</h3>

<pre><code>.product-card > .title {
    margin: 0;
}</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Use shallow scoped component selectors.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Specificity escalation</h2>

        <div class="anti-pattern-pair">
            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--bad">
                <h3>Problem</h3>

<pre><code>#app .product-list .product-card .title {
    color: red !important;
}</code></pre>

                <p>
                    IDs and important declarations create override battles.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--good">
                <h3>Fix</h3>

<pre><code>@layer components, theme;

@layer theme {
    .product-card > .title {
        color: red;
    }
}</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Use layer order before increasing specificity.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Utility overload
        </h2>

        <div class="anti-pattern-pair">
            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--bad">
                <h3>Problem</h3>

<pre><code>&lt;article class="p-l m-b-xl bg-dark text-light radius-m grid gap-m"&gt;
    ...
&lt;/article&gt;</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Too many utilities can hide component intent.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--good">
                <h3>Fix</h3>

<pre><code>&lt;article class="product-card product-card--featured"&gt;
    ...
&lt;/article&gt;</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Use semantic components and reserve utilities for small,
                    clear helpers.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Massive root files
        </h2>

        <div class="anti-pattern-pair">
            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--bad">
                <h3>Problem</h3>

<pre><code>site.css
    8,000 lines
    all components
    all layouts
    all hacks</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Large root files make ownership and review harder.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--good">
                <h3>Fix</h3>

<pre><code>components/
    product-card.css
    site-header.css
    filter-panel.css</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Keep root files as import maps, not dumping grounds.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Third-party CSS leakage
        </h2>

        <div class="anti-pattern-pair">
            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--bad">
                <h3>Problem</h3>

<pre><code>@import './vendor/slider.css';</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Unlayered third-party CSS can unexpectedly dominate your
                    project styles.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="anti-pattern-card anti-pattern-card--good">
                <h3>Fix</h3>

<pre><code>@import './vendor/slider.css' layer(legacy);</code></pre>

                <p>
                    Isolate third-party CSS in a low-priority layer.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
